knowledge_graph.title: Giant Pacific octopus
knowledge_graph.description: The giant Pacific octopus, also known as the North Pacific giant octopus, is a large marine cephalopod belonging to the genus Enteroctopus and Enteroctopodidae family.

related_questions.question: How big is a North Pacific giant octopus?
related_questions.snippet: Astounding anatomy. This octopus is impressive in size. A full-grown giant Pacific octopus can weigh more than 50 pounds. The heaviest on record was a creature weighing 200 pounds and measuring nearly 20 feet across.
related_questions.title: Giant Pacific octopus | Animals - Monterey Bay Aquarium

related_questions.question: How venomous is a giant Pacific octopus?
related_questions.snippet: Is the Giant Pacific Octopus' venom hazardous to humans or just other marine wildlife? Yes, the venom is hazardous to both humans and marine life - hazardous, but not deadly to humans.
related_questions.title: OctoFAQ | Oregon Sea Grant

related_questions.question: What's the biggest octopus ever found?
related_questions.snippet: The giant Pacific octopus grows bigger and lives longer than any other octopus species. The size record is held by a specimen that was 30 feet across and weighed more than 600 pounds. Averages are more like 16 feet and 110 lbs.
related_questions.title: Giant Pacific Octopus | National Geographic

related_questions.question: Does anything eat the giant Pacific octopus?
related_questions.snippet: Seals, sea otters, sharks, and large fish are the predominant predators of the giant Pacific octopus. The giant Pacific octopus is an intelligent animal with a well-developed brain.
